Our method for balancing dataset and justification

We decided to balance the dataset by categorizing the Child Poverty value into 4 different instances. To get the exact same number of instances into every class, we first sorted the dataframe according to Child Poverty values in ascending order and then got the value of Child Poverty from four equidistant indexes throughout the table. To explain the mathematics a bit, there were 72718 rows in the table, so we divided this number by 4 to get 18179.5. Then we got the values of the table at indices 18179, 36359, 54549, and 72717 so that we would be grabbing exactly a quarter of the total samples each time. We decided to use this method so that every single class would have the exact same number of instances. We then changed the target to have the integers 0, 1, 2, and 3, with 0 being 0-6.2%, 1 being 6.2-16.3%, 2 being 16.3%-31.6% and 3 being 31.6%-100%.

Should balancing of the dataset be done for both the training and testing set?

Yes and no. It depends on how you define balancing. In our case, we decided to balance the dataset into classes, not by creating new samples of underrepresented data or deleting overrepresented data, but by separating the existing data into even groups. In this case, yes, you want to do it for both the training and testing sets, so that they are encoded in similar ways and there is no confusion in the classifier. However, there is also the possibility that by 'balancing' you mean deleting overrepresented data or increasing underrepresented data. The requirement was sort of unclear in that general area, but if this was the intention, then no, you would not balance the dataset in the testing set because you would want to test your algorithm on a testing set that was true-to-life and not manipulated.

# Using examples from class
class TwoLayerPerceptronBase(object): #MSE loss
    def __init__(self, n_hidden=5,
                 C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None):
        np.random.seed(random_state)
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden
        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        """Encode labels into one-hot representation"""
        onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
            
        return onehot

    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights with small random numbers."""
        W1_num_elems = (self.n_features_)*self.n_hidden
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W1_num_elems)
        W1 = W1.reshape(self.n_hidden, self.n_features_) # reshape to be W
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        
        W2_num_elems = (self.n_hidden)*self.n_output_
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W2_num_elems)
        W2 = W2.reshape(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, b1, b2
    
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(z):
        """Use scipy.special.expit to avoid overflow"""
        # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
        return expit(z)
    
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W1, W2):
        """Compute L2-regularization cost"""
        # only compute for non-bias terms
        return (lambda_/2.0) * np.sqrt(np.mean(W1[:, 1:] ** 2) + np.mean(W2[:, 1:] ** 2))
    
    def _cost(self,A3,Y_enc,W1,W2):
        '''Get the objective function value'''
        cost = np.mean((Y_enc-A3)**2) 
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _feedforward(self, X, W1, W2, b1, b2):
        """Compute feedforward step
        -----------
        X : Input layer with original features.
        W1: Weight matrix for input layer -> hidden layer.
        W2: Weight matrix for hidden layer -> output layer.
        ----------
        a1-a3 : activations into layer (or output layer)
        z1-z2 : layer inputs 

        """
        A1 = X.T
        Z1 = W1 @ A1 + b1

        A2 = self._sigmoid(Z1)

        Z2 = W2 @ A2 + b2

        A3 = self._sigmoid(Z2)
        #
        #Z3 = W3 @ A3 + b3

        return A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, Z1, Z2, Y_enc, W1, W2):
        """ Compute gradient step using backpropagation.
        """
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V2 = -2*(Y_enc-A3)*A3*(1-A3)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradb1, gradb2
    
    def predict(self, X):
        """Predict class labels"""
        _, _, _, _, A3 = self._feedforward(X, self.W1, self.W2, self.b1, self.b2)

        # assert False, A3.shape

        y_pred = np.argmax(A3, axis=0)
        return y_pred

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
# just start with the vectorized version and minibatch
class TLPMiniBatch(TwoLayerPerceptronBase):  #MSE loss
    def __init__(self, alpha=0.0, decrease_const=0.1, 
                 decrease_iter = 10, shuffle=True, 
                 minibatches=1, **kwds):        
        # need to add to the original initializer 
        self.alpha = alpha
        self.decrease_const = decrease_const
        self.decrease_iter = decrease_iter
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.minibatches = minibatches
        # but keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False, XY_test=None):
        """ Learn weights from training data. With mini-batch"""
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.b1, self.b2 = self._initialize_weights()

        # start momentum at zero for previous updates
        rho_W1_prev = np.zeros(self.W1.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W2_prev = np.zeros(self.W2.shape) # for momentum

        self.cost_ = []
        self.score_ = []
        # get starting acc
        self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))

        # keep track of validation, if given
        if XY_test is not None:
            X_test = XY_test[0].copy()
            y_test = XY_test[1].copy()
            self.val_score_ = []
            self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            self.val_cost_ = []
            
        for i in range(self.epochs):

            # adaptive learning rate
            # decrease at certain epochs
            eta = self.eta * self.decrease_const**(np.floor(i/self.decrease_iter))

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            if self.shuffle:
                idx_shuffle = np.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc, y_data = X_data[idx_shuffle], Y_enc[:, idx_shuffle], y_data[idx_shuffle]

            mini = np.array_split(range(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []
            for idx in mini:

                # feedforward
                A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3 = self._feedforward(X_data[idx],
                                                       self.W1,
                                                       self.W2,
                                                       self.b1,
                                                       self.b2
                                                      )
                
                cost = self._cost(A3,Y_enc[:, idx],self.W1,self.W2)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                gradW1, gradW2, gradb1, gradb2 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, 
                                                  Y_enc=Y_enc[:, idx],
                                                  W1=self.W1,W2=self.W2)

                # momentum calculations
                rho_W1, rho_W2 = eta * gradW1, eta * gradW2
                self.W1 -= (rho_W1 + (self.alpha * rho_W1_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W2 -= (rho_W2 + (self.alpha * rho_W2_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.b1 -= eta * gradb1
                self.b2 -= eta * gradb2
                rho_W1_prev, rho_W2_prev = rho_W1, rho_W2
                

            self.cost_.append(np.mean(mini_cost))
            self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
            if XY_test is not None:
                yhat = self.predict(X_test)
                self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,yhat))
            
        return self

# to implement the new style of objective function, 
# we just need to update the final layer calculation of the gradient
class TLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy(TLPMiniBatch):  #CrossEntropy loss
    def _cost(self,A3,Y_enc,W1,W2):
        '''Get the objective function value'''
        cost = -np.mean(np.nan_to_num((Y_enc*np.log(A3)+(1-Y_enc)*np.log(1-A3))))
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, Z1, Z2, Y_enc, W1, W2):
        """ Compute gradient step using backpropagation.
        """
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V2 = (A3-Y_enc) # <- this is only line that changed
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradb1, gradb2

class TLPBetterInitialCrossEntropy(TLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy):   #CrossEntropy loss        
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights Glorot and He normalization."""
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden + self.n_features_))
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden, self.n_features_))

        # reduce the final layer magnitude in order to balance the size of the gradients
        # between 
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_output_ + self.n_hidden))
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)) 
        
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, b1, b2

class TLPBetterInitialMSE(TLPMiniBatch):   #MSE loss        
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights Glorot and He normalization."""
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden + self.n_features_))
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden, self.n_features_))

        # reduce the final layer magnitude in order to balance the size of the gradients
        # between 
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_output_ + self.n_hidden))
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden))

        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, b1, b2

def print_result(nn,X_train,y_train,X_test,y_test,title="",color="red"):
    
    print("=================")
    print(title,":")
    yhat = nn.predict(X_train)
    print('Resubstitution acc:',accuracy_score(y_train,yhat))
    
    yhat = nn.predict(X_test)
    print('Validation acc:',accuracy_score(y_test,yhat))
    
    if hasattr(nn,'val_score_'):
        plt.plot(range(len(nn.val_score_)), nn.val_score_, color=color,label=title)
        plt.ylabel('Validation Accuracy')
    else:
        plt.plot(range(len(nn.score_)), nn.score_, color=color,label=title)
        plt.ylabel('Resub Accuracy')
        
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.grid(True)

This took way longer to run and got around the same accuracy as the data that was just normalized but not one hot encoded. It was a tiny bit lower with CrossEntropy but higher with MSE. One hot encoding is necessary because if the target is represented as integer encoding, then the network will place a higher value to targets with a larger number and a lower value to targets with a lower number, which we don’t want. Therefore, both normalization and one hot encoding are needed to have reliable results. The reason one hot encoding probably took a lot longer was because adding all of those vectorized encodings creates many new columns that the algorithm has to process individually.

Analysis

Out of the three methods (no normalization or one hot encoding, normalization but no one hot encoding, both normalization and one hot encoding), the one that performed the best was the method of both normalization and one hot encoding. That is, it performed best according to accuracy. It performed the worst in terms of runtime. We think that normalization improved the graphing the most because the different data values had such different scalings that normalizing them changed the data proportions greatly and therefore led to a more accurate graph without any bias towards one particular value. Additionally, we noted that the class example of the MLP included encoding, but we did not want to mess with the functions provided in class. However, this may have skewed results somewhat.

Next up is modeling 3 layer, 4 layer, and 5 layer networks, along with an adaptive learning technique.

Modeling¶

To create a 3 layer network, we added an extra hidden layer in the middle, named n_hidden2. We decided to make this new hidden layer contain 30 neurons and the previous hidden layer contain 15 neurons so that it would run quicker, because if the layers have large amounts of neurons, the algorithm has a very large runtime.

# 3 layer
class ThreeLayerPerceptronBase(object):
    def __init__(self, n_hidden=15, n_hidden2 = 30,
                 C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None):
        np.random.seed(random_state)
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden
        self.n_hidden2 = n_hidden2
        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        """Encode labels into one-hot representation"""
        onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
            
        return onehot

    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights with small random numbers."""
        W1_num_elems = (self.n_features_)*self.n_hidden2
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W1_num_elems)
        W1 = W1.reshape(self.n_hidden2, self.n_features_) # reshape to be W
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden2, 1))
        
        W2_num_elems = (self.n_hidden2)*self.n_hidden
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W2_num_elems)
        W2 = W2.reshape(self.n_hidden, self.n_hidden2)
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        
        W3_num_elems = (self.n_hidden)*self.n_output_
        W3 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W3_num_elems)
        W3 = W3.reshape(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)
        b3 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, W3, b1, b2, b3
    
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(z):
        """Use scipy.special.expit to avoid overflow"""
        # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
        return expit(z)
    
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W1, W2, W3):
        """Compute L2-regularization cost"""
        # only compute for non-bias terms
        return (lambda_/2.0) * np.sqrt(np.mean(W1[:, 1:] ** 2) + np.mean(W2[:, 1:] ** 2) + np.mean(W3[:, 1:] ** 2))
    
    def _cost(self,A3,Y_enc,W1,W2, W3):
        '''Get the objective function value'''
        cost = np.mean((Y_enc-A3)**2)
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2, W3)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _feedforward(self, X, W1, W2, W3, b1, b2, b3):
        """Compute feedforward step
        -----------
        X : Input layer with original features.
        W1: Weight matrix for input layer -> hidden layer.
        W2: Weight matrix for hidden layer -> output layer.
        ----------
        a1-a3 : activations into layer (or output layer)
        z1-z2 : layer inputs 

        """
        A1 = X.T
        Z1 = W1 @ A1 + b1
        A2 = self._sigmoid(Z1)
        Z2 = W2 @ A2 + b2
        A3 = self._sigmoid(Z2)
        Z3 = W3 @ A3 + b3
        A4 = self._sigmoid(Z3)
        return A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, Z1, Z2, Z3, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3):
        """ Compute gradient step using backpropagation.
        """
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V3 = -2*(Y_enc-A4)*A4*(1-A4)
        V2 = A3*(1-A3)*(W3.T @ V3)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C
        gradW3 += W3 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3
    
    def predict(self, X):
        """Predict class labels"""
        _, _, _, _, _, _, A4 = self._feedforward(X, self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3)
        y_pred = np.argmax(A4, axis=0)
        return y_pred

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
# just start with the vectorized version and minibatch
class TLPMiniBatch(ThreeLayerPerceptronBase):  #MSE loss
    def __init__(self, alpha=0.0, decrease_const=0.1, 
                 decrease_iter = 10, shuffle=True, 
                 minibatches=1,save_grad={}, **kwds):        
        # need to add to the original initializer 
        self.alpha = alpha
        self.decrease_const = decrease_const
        self.decrease_iter = decrease_iter
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.minibatches = minibatches
        self.save_grad = save_grad
        # but keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False, XY_test=None):
        """ Learn weights from training data. With mini-batch"""
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3 = self._initialize_weights()

        # start momentum at zero for previous updates
        rho_W1_prev = np.zeros(self.W1.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W2_prev = np.zeros(self.W2.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W3_prev = np.zeros(self.W3.shape)

        self.cost_ = []
        self.score_ = []
        # get starting acc
        self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))

        # keep track of validation, if given
        if XY_test is not None:
            X_test = XY_test[0].copy()
            y_test = XY_test[1].copy()
            self.val_score_ = []
            self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            self.val_cost_ = []
        self.save_grad = {}

        for i in range(self.epochs):

            # adaptive learning rate
            # decrease at certain epochs
            eta = self.eta * self.decrease_const**(np.floor(i/self.decrease_iter))

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            if self.shuffle:
                idx_shuffle = np.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc, y_data = X_data[idx_shuffle], Y_enc[:, idx_shuffle], y_data[idx_shuffle]

            mini = np.array_split(range(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []
            for idx in mini:

                # feedforward
                A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4 = self._feedforward(X_data[idx],
                                                       self.W1,
                                                       self.W2,
                                                       self.W3,
                                                       self.b1,
                                                       self.b2,
                                                       self.b3
                                                      )
                
                cost = self._cost(A4,Y_enc[:, idx],self.W1,self.W2, self.W3)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, A4=A4,
                                                                                    Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Z3=Z3,
                                                                                      Y_enc=Y_enc[:, idx],
                                                                                      W1=self.W1,W2=self.W2,W3=self.W3)
                self.save_grad[i] = [np.mean(gradb1), np.mean(gradb2), np.mean(gradb3)]
                # momentum calculations
                rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3 = eta * gradW1, eta * gradW2, eta * gradW3
                self.W1 -= (rho_W1 + (self.alpha * rho_W1_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W2 -= (rho_W2 + (self.alpha * rho_W2_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W3 -= (rho_W3 + (self.alpha * rho_W3_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.b1 -= eta * gradb1
                self.b2 -= eta * gradb2
                self.b3 -= eta * gradb3
                rho_W1_prev, rho_W2_prev, rho_W3_prev = rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3
                

            self.cost_.append(np.mean(mini_cost))
            self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
            if XY_test is not None:
                yhat = self.predict(X_test)
                self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,yhat))
            
        return self

# to implement the new style of objective function, 
# we just need to update the final layer calculation of the gradient
class TLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy(TLPMiniBatch):  #CrossEntropy loss
    def _cost(self,A4,Y_enc,W1,W2,W3):
        '''Get the objective function value'''
        cost = -np.mean(np.nan_to_num((Y_enc*np.log(A4)+(1-Y_enc)*np.log(1-A4))))
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2, W3)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, Z1, Z2, Z3, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3):
        """ Compute gradient step using backpropagation.
        """
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V3 = A4-Y_enc
        V2 = A3*(1-A3)*(W3.T @ V3) # <- this is only line that changed
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C
        gradW3 += W3 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3

class TLPBetterInitialCrossEntropy(TLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy):   #CrossEntropy loss        
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights Glorot and He normalization."""
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden2 + self.n_features_))
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden2, self.n_features_))

        # reduce the final layer magnitude in order to balance the size of the gradients
        # between 
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden + self.n_hidden2))
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden, self.n_hidden2)) 
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_output_ + self.n_hidden))
        W3 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)) 

        
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden2, 1))
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        b3 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, W3, b1, b2, b3

Our 3 layer network performs better than our 2 layer network! Next, we'll see if we can improve performance even more with a 4 layer network.

To create a 4 layer network, we added another hidden layer in the middle, named n_hidden3. This layer is closest to the features so it will be the largest hidden layer, at 30 neurons. We decided to make the other hidden layers contain 20 and 10 neurons so that the algorithm would run quicker, because if the layers have large amounts of neurons, the algorithm has a very large runtime.

# 4 layer
class FourLayerPerceptronBase(object):
    def __init__(self, n_hidden=10, n_hidden2 = 20, n_hidden3 = 30,
                 C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None):
        np.random.seed(random_state)
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden
        self.n_hidden2 = n_hidden2
        self.n_hidden3 = n_hidden3
        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        """Encode labels into one-hot representation"""
        onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
            
        return onehot

    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights with small random numbers."""
        W1_num_elems = (self.n_features_)*self.n_hidden3
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W1_num_elems)
        W1 = W1.reshape(self.n_hidden3, self.n_features_) # reshape to be W
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden2, 1))
        
        W2_num_elems = (self.n_hidden3)*self.n_hidden2
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W2_num_elems)
        W2 = W2.reshape(self.n_hidden2, self.n_hidden3)
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        
        W3_num_elems = (self.n_hidden2)*self.n_hidden
        W3 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W3_num_elems)
        W3 = W3.reshape(self.n_hidden, self.n_hidden2)
        b3 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        W4_num_elems = (self.n_hidden)*self.n_output_
        W4 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W4_num_elems)
        W4 = W4.reshape(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)
        b4 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, W3, W4, b1, b2, b3, b4
    
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(z):
        """Use scipy.special.expit to avoid overflow"""
        # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
        return expit(z)
    
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W1, W2, W3, W4):
        """Compute L2-regularization cost"""
        # only compute for non-bias terms
        return (lambda_/2.0) * np.sqrt(np.mean(W1[:, 1:] ** 2) + np.mean(W2[:, 1:] ** 2) + np.mean(W3[:, 1:] ** 2) + np.mean(W4[:, 1:]**2))

    def _cost(self,A4,Y_enc,W1,W2, W3, W4):
        '''Get the objective function value'''
        cost = np.mean((Y_enc-A4)**2)
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2, W3, W4)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _feedforward(self, X, W1, W2, W3, W4, b1, b2, b3, b4):
        """Compute feedforward step
        -----------
        X : Input layer with original features.
        W1: Weight matrix for input layer -> hidden layer.
        W2: Weight matrix for hidden layer -> output layer.
        ----------
        a1-a3 : activations into layer (or output layer)
        z1-z2 : layer inputs 

        """
        A1 = X.T
        Z1 = W1 @ A1 + b1
        A2 = self._sigmoid(Z1)
        Z2 = W2 @ A2 + b2
        A3 = self._sigmoid(Z2)
        Z3 = W3 @ A3 + b3
        A4 = self._sigmoid(Z3)
        Z4 = W4 @ A4 + b4
        A5 = self._sigmoid(Z4)
                                       
        return A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, Z1, Z2, Z3, Z4, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3, W4):
        """ Compute gradient step using backpropagation.
        """
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V4 = -2*(Y_enc-A5)*A5*(1-A5)
        V3 = A4*(1-A4)*(W4.T @ V4)
        V2 = A3*(1-A3)*(W3.T @ V3)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        gradW4 = V4 @ A4.T
        
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb4 = np.sum(V4, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
                                       
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C
        gradW3 += W3 * self.l2_C
        gradW4 += W4 * self.l2_C
                                       
        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4
    
    def predict(self, X):
        """Predict class labels"""
        _, _, _, _, _, _, _, _, A5 = self._feedforward(X, self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3, self.b4)
        y_pred = np.argmax(A5, axis=0)
        return y_pred

# just start with the vectorized version and minibatch
class TLPMiniBatch(FourLayerPerceptronBase):  #MSE loss
    def __init__(self, alpha=0.0, decrease_const=0.1, 
                 decrease_iter = 10, shuffle=True, 
                 minibatches=1,save_grad={}, **kwds):        
        # need to add to the original initializer 
        self.alpha = alpha
        self.decrease_const = decrease_const
        self.decrease_iter = decrease_iter
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.minibatches = minibatches
        self.save_grad = save_grad
        # but keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False, XY_test=None):
        """ Learn weights from training data. With mini-batch"""
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3, self.b4 = self._initialize_weights()

        # start momentum at zero for previous updates
        rho_W1_prev = np.zeros(self.W1.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W2_prev = np.zeros(self.W2.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W3_prev = np.zeros(self.W3.shape)
        rho_W4_prev = np.zeros(self.W4.shape)

        self.cost_ = []
        self.score_ = []
        # get starting acc
        self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))

        # keep track of validation, if given
        if XY_test is not None:
            X_test = XY_test[0].copy()
            y_test = XY_test[1].copy()
            self.val_score_ = []
            self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            self.val_cost_ = []
        self.save_grad = {}
        for i in range(self.epochs):

            # adaptive learning rate
            # decrease at certain epochs
            eta = self.eta * self.decrease_const**(np.floor(i/self.decrease_iter))

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            if self.shuffle:
                idx_shuffle = np.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc, y_data = X_data[idx_shuffle], Y_enc[:, idx_shuffle], y_data[idx_shuffle]

            mini = np.array_split(range(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []
            for idx in mini:

                # feedforward
                A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5 = self._feedforward(X_data[idx],
                                                       self.W1,
                                                       self.W2,
                                                       self.W3,
                                                        self.W4,
                                                       self.b1,
                                                       self.b2,
                                                       self.b3,
                                                        self.b4
                                                      )
                
                cost = self._cost(A5,Y_enc[:, idx],self.W1,self.W2, self.W3, self.W4)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4= self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, A4=A4,
                                                                                                   A5=A5,
                                                                                    Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Z3=Z3, Z4=Z4,
                                                                                      Y_enc=Y_enc[:, idx],
                                                                                      W1=self.W1,W2=self.W2,W3=self.W3,
                                                                                                  W4=self.W4)
                self.save_grad[i] = [np.mean(gradb1), np.mean(gradb2), np.mean(gradb3),np.mean(gradb4)]
                # momentum calculations
                rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3, rho_W4 = eta * gradW1, eta * gradW2, eta * gradW3, eta * gradW4
                self.W1 -= (rho_W1 + (self.alpha * rho_W1_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W2 -= (rho_W2 + (self.alpha * rho_W2_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W3 -= (rho_W3 + (self.alpha * rho_W3_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W4 -= (rho_W4 + (self.alpha * rho_W4_prev))
                self.b1 -= eta * gradb1
                self.b2 -= eta * gradb2
                self.b3 -= eta * gradb3
                self.b4 -= eta * gradb4
                rho_W1_prev, rho_W2_prev, rho_W3_prev, rho_W4_prev = rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3, rho_W4
                

            self.cost_.append(np.mean(mini_cost))
            self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
            if XY_test is not None:
                yhat = self.predict(X_test)
                self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,yhat))
            
        return self

# to implement the new style of objective function, 
# we just need to update the final layer calculation of the gradient
class TLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy(TLPMiniBatch):  #CrossEntropy loss
    def _cost(self,A5,Y_enc,W1,W2,W3, W4):
        '''Get the objective function value'''
        cost = -np.mean(np.nan_to_num((Y_enc*np.log(A5)+(1-Y_enc)*np.log(1-A5))))
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2, W3, W4)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, Z1, Z2, Z3, Z4, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3, W4):
        """ Compute gradient step using backpropagation.
        """
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V4 = A5-Y_enc
        V3 = A4*(1-A4)*(W4.T @ V4)
        V2 = A3*(1-A3)*(W3.T @ V3) # <- this is only line that changed
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW4 = V4 @ A4.T
        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb4 = np.sum(V4, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C
        gradW3 += W3 * self.l2_C
        gradW4 += W4 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4

class TLPBetterInitialCrossEntropy(TLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy):   #CrossEntropy loss        
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights Glorot and He normalization."""
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden3 + self.n_features_))
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden3, self.n_features_))

        # reduce the final layer magnitude in order to balance the size of the gradients
        # between 
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden2 + self.n_hidden3))
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden2, self.n_hidden3)) 
        
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden + self.n_hidden2))        
        W3 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden, self.n_hidden2)) 
        
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_output_ + self.n_hidden))        
        W4 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)) 
        
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden3, 1))
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden2, 1))
        b3 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        b4 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, W3, W4, b1, b2, b3, b4

Our 4 layer network performs about the same as our 3 layer network, if not the tinest fraction of a percentage better. Finally, we'll see if we can improve performance even more with a 5 layer network.

To create a 5 layer network, we added another hidden layer in the middle, named n_hidden4. This layer is closest to the features so it will be the largest hidden layer, at 30 neurons. We decided to make the other hidden layers contain 20, 10, and 5 neurons so that the algorithm would run quicker, because if the layers have large amounts of neurons, the algorithm has a very large runtime.

# 5 layer
class FiveLayerPerceptronBase(object):
    def __init__(self, n_hidden=5, n_hidden2 = 15, n_hidden3 = 20, n_hidden4 = 30,
                 C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None):
        np.random.seed(random_state)
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden
        self.n_hidden2 = n_hidden2
        self.n_hidden3 = n_hidden3
        self.n_hidden4 = n_hidden4
        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        """Encode labels into one-hot representation"""
        onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
            
        return onehot

    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights with small random numbers."""
        W1_num_elems = (self.n_features_)*self.n_hidden4
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W1_num_elems)
        W1 = W1.reshape(self.n_hidden4, self.n_features_) # reshape to be W
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden4, 1))
        
        W2_num_elems = (self.n_hidden4)*self.n_hidden3
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W2_num_elems)
        W2 = W2.reshape(self.n_hidden3, self.n_hidden4)
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden3, 1))
        
        W3_num_elems = (self.n_hidden3)*self.n_hidden2
        W3 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W3_num_elems)
        W3 = W3.reshape(self.n_hidden2, self.n_hidden3)
        b3 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden2, 1))
        
        W4_num_elems = (self.n_hidden2)*self.n_hidden
        W4 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W4_num_elems)
        W4 = W4.reshape(self.n_hidden, self.n_hidden2)
        b4 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        
        W5_num_elems = (self.n_hidden)*self.n_output_
        W5 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W5_num_elems)
        W5 = W5.reshape(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)
        b5 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, W3, W4, W5, b1, b2, b3, b4, b5
    
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(z):
        """Use scipy.special.expit to avoid overflow"""
        # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
        return expit(z)
    
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5):
        """Compute L2-regularization cost"""
        # only compute for non-bias terms
        return (lambda_/2.0) * np.sqrt(np.mean(W1[:, 1:] ** 2) + np.mean(W2[:, 1:] ** 2) + np.mean(W3[:, 1:] ** 2) + np.mean(W4[:, 1:]**2) + np.mean(W4[:, 1:]**2))

    def _cost(self,A5,Y_enc,W1,W2, W3, W4, W5):
        '''Get the objective function value'''
        cost = np.mean((Y_enc-A5)**2)
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _feedforward(self, X, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5, b1, b2, b3, b4, b5):
        """Compute feedforward step
        -----------
        X : Input layer with original features.
        W1: Weight matrix for input layer -> hidden layer.
        W2: Weight matrix for hidden layer -> output layer.
        ----------
        a1-a3 : activations into layer (or output layer)
        z1-z2 : layer inputs 

        """
        A1 = X.T
        Z1 = W1 @ A1 + b1
        A2 = self._sigmoid(Z1)
        Z2 = W2 @ A2 + b2
        A3 = self._sigmoid(Z2)
        Z3 = W3 @ A3 + b3
        A4 = self._sigmoid(Z3)
        Z4 = W4 @ A4 + b4
        A5 = self._sigmoid(Z4)
        Z5 = W5 @ A5 + b5
        A6 = self._sigmoid(Z5)
                                       
        return A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5, Z5, A6
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, A6, Z1, Z2, Z3, Z4, Z5, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5):
        """ Compute gradient step using backpropagation.
        """
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V5 = -2*(Y_enc-A6)*A6*(1-A6)
        V4 = A5*(1-A5)*(W5.T @ V5)
        V3 = A4*(1-A4)*(W4.T @ V4)
        V2 = A3*(1-A3)*(W3.T @ V3)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        gradW4 = V4 @ A4.T
        gradW5 = V5 @ A5.T
        
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb4 = np.sum(V4, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb5 = np.sum(V5, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
                                       
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C
        gradW3 += W3 * self.l2_C
        gradW4 += W4 * self.l2_C
        gradW5 += W5 * self.l2_C
                               
        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradW5, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4, gradb5
    
    def predict(self, X):
        """Predict class labels"""
        _, _, _, _, _, _, _, _, _, _, A6 = self._feedforward(X, self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.W5, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3, self.b4, self.b5)
        y_pred = np.argmax(A6, axis=0)
        return y_pred

class TLPMiniBatch_Adp(FiveLayerPerceptronBase):  #MSE loss
    def __init__(self, alpha=0.0, decrease_const=0.1, 
                 decrease_iter = 10, shuffle=True,

        self.minibatches = minibatches
        self.save_grad = save_grad

        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.W5, self.b1, self.b2, self.b3, self.b4, self.b5 = self._initialize_weights()

        # start momentum at zero for previous updates
        rho_W1_prev = np.zeros(self.W1.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W2_prev = np.zeros(self.W2.shape) # for momentum
        rho_W3_prev = np.zeros(self.W3.shape)
        rho_W4_prev = np.zeros(self.W4.shape)
        rho_W5_prev = np.zeros(self.W5.shape)

        self.cost_ = []
        self.score_ = []
        # get starting acc
        self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))

        # keep track of validation, if given
        if XY_test is not None:
            X_test = XY_test[0].copy()
            y_test = XY_test[1].copy()
            self.val_score_ = []
            self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            self.val_cost_ = []
        self.save_grad = {} 
        for i in range(self.epochs):

            # adaptive learning rate
            # decrease at certain epochs
            eta = self.eta * self.decrease_const**(np.floor(i/self.decrease_iter))

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            if self.shuffle:
                idx_shuffle = np.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc, y_data = X_data[idx_shuffle], Y_enc[:, idx_shuffle], y_data[idx_shuffle]

            mini = np.array_split(range(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []
            for idx in mini:

                # feedforward
                A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5, Z5, A6 = self._feedforward(X_data[idx],
                                                       self.W1,
                                                       self.W2,
                                                       self.W3,
                                                        self.W4,
                                                        self.W5,
                                                       self.b1,
                                                       self.b2,
                                                       self.b3,
                                                        self.b4,
                                                         self.b5                      
                                                      )
                
                cost = self._cost(A6,Y_enc[:, idx],self.W1,self.W2, self.W3, self.W4, self.W5)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradW5, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4, gradb5= self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, A4=A4,
                                                                                                   A5=A5, A6=A6,
                                                                                    Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, Z3=Z3, Z4=Z4, Z5=Z5,
                                                                                      Y_enc=Y_enc[:, idx],
                                                                                      W1=self.W1,W2=self.W2,W3=self.W3,
                                                                                                  W4=self.W4, W5=self.W5)
                self.save_grad[i] = [np.mean(gradb1), np.mean(gradb2), np.mean(gradb3), np.mean(gradb4), np.mean(gradb5)]
                # momentum calculations
                rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3, rho_W4, rho_W5 = eta * gradW1, eta * gradW2, eta * gradW3, eta * gradW4, eta * gradW5
                self.W1 -= (rho_W1 + (self.alpha * rho_W1_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W2 -= (rho_W2 + (self.alpha * rho_W2_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W3 -= (rho_W3 + (self.alpha * rho_W3_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W4 -= (rho_W4 + (self.alpha * rho_W4_prev))
                self.W5 -= (rho_W5 + (self.alpha * rho_W5_prev))
               
                self.b1 -= eta * gradb1
                self.b2 -= eta * gradb2
                self.b3 -= eta * gradb3
                self.b4 -= eta * gradb4
                self.b5 -= eta * gradb5
                rho_W1_prev, rho_W2_prev, rho_W3_prev, rho_W4_prev, rho_W5_prev = rho_W1, rho_W2, rho_W3, rho_W4, rho_W5
                

            self.cost_.append(np.mean(mini_cost))
            self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
            if XY_test is not None:
                yhat = self.predict(X_test)
                self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,yhat))
            
        return self

# to implement the new style of objective function, 
# we just need to update the final layer calculation of the gradient
class TLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy(TLPMiniBatch):  #CrossEntropy loss
    def _cost(self,A6,Y_enc,W1,W2,W3, W4, W5):
        '''Get the objective function value'''
        cost = -np.mean(np.nan_to_num((Y_enc*np.log(A6)+(1-Y_enc)*np.log(1-A6))))
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, A6, Z1, Z2, Z3, Z4, Z5, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5):
        """ Compute gradient step using backpropagation.
        """
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V5 = A6-Y_enc
        V4 = A5*(1-A5)*(W5.T @ V5)
        V3 = A4*(1-A4)*(W4.T @ V4)
        V2 = A3*(1-A3)*(W3.T @ V3) # <- this is only line that changed
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW5 = V5 @ A5.T
        gradW4 = V4 @ A4.T
        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T

        gradb5 = np.sum(V5, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))        
        gradb4 = np.sum(V4, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C
        gradW3 += W3 * self.l2_C
        gradW4 += W4 * self.l2_C
        gradW5 += W5 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradW5, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4, gradb5

class TLPBetterInitialCrossEntropy(TLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy):   #CrossEntropy loss        
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights Glorot and He normalization."""
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden4 + self.n_features_))
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden4, self.n_features_))

        # reduce the final layer magnitude in order to balance the size of the gradients
        # between 
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden3 + self.n_hidden4))
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden3, self.n_hidden4)) 
        
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden2 + self.n_hidden3))        
        W3 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden2, self.n_hidden3)) 
        
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden2 + self.n_hidden))
        W4 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden, self.n_hidden2)) 
        
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_output_ + self.n_hidden))
        W5 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)) 

        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden4, 1))
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden3, 1))
        b3 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden2, 1))
        b4 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        b5 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, W3, W4, W5, b1, b2, b3, b4, b5

# adaptive
class TLPReLU(TLPBetterInitialMSE):
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden4 + self.n_features_))
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden4, self.n_features_))

        # reduce the final layer magnitude in order to balance the size of the gradients
        # between 
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden3 + self.n_hidden4))
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden3, self.n_hidden4)) 
        
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden2 + self.n_hidden3))        
        W3 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden2, self.n_hidden3)) 
        
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_hidden2 + self.n_hidden))
        W4 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden, self.n_hidden2)) 
        
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_output_ + self.n_hidden))
        W5 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)) 

        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden4, 1))
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden3, 1))
        b3 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden2, 1))
        b4 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        b5 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, W3, W4, W5, b1, b2, b3, b4, b5
    
    @staticmethod
    def _relu(Z):
        return np.maximum(0, Z.copy())
        
    def _feedforward(self, X, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5, b1, b2, b3, b4, b5):
        """Compute feedforward step
        """
        # A1->W1->ReLu->A2->W2->Sigmoid
        A1 = X.T
        Z1 = W1 @ A1 + b1
        A2 = self._relu(Z1)
        Z2 = W2 @ A2 + b2
        A3 = self._relu(Z2)
        Z3 = W3 @ A3 + b3
        A4 = self._relu(Z3)
        Z4 = W4 @ A4 + b4
        A5 = self._relu(Z4)
        Z5 = W5 @ A5 + b5
        A6 = self._sigmoid(Z5) # never use relu as last layer for classification (yuck!)
        return A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3, Z3, A4, Z4, A5, Z5, A6
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, A6, Z1, Z2, Z3, Z4, Z5, Y_enc, W1, W2, W3, W4, W5):
        """ Compute gradient step using backpropagation.
        """
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V5 = (A6-Y_enc) 
        
        # V3[Z2<=0] = 0 # could can change to be relu back prop on this layer too!
        
        # old update: V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        # the derivative of sigmoid was A2(1-A2), but now that is relu
        # so we change it to:
        
        V4 = (W5.T @ V5) 
        V4[Z4<=0] = 0
        
        V3 = (W4.T @ V4) 
        V3[Z3<=0] = 0
        
        V2 = (W3.T @ V3) 
        V2[Z2<=0] = 0
        
        V1 = (W2.T @ V2) 
        V1[Z1<=0] = 0
        # relu derivative only zeros out certain values! easy!
        
        gradW5 = V5 @ A5.T
        gradW4 = V4 @ A4.T
        gradW3 = V3 @ A3.T
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb5 = np.sum(V5, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb4 = np.sum(V4, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb3 = np.sum(V3, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))        
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += (W1 * self.l2_C)
        gradW2 += (W2 * self.l2_C)
        gradW3 += (W3 * self.l2_C)
        gradW4 += (W4 * self.l2_C)
        gradW5 += (W5 * self.l2_C)        

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradW3, gradW4, gradW5, gradb1, gradb2, gradb3, gradb4, gradb5

Comparisons¶

The ReLU did not perform well at all, with an acccuracy around 25%. This is about the same as the 2 layer network performed when the data was neither normalized nor one hot encoded. This goes to show that this adaptive learning rate was not very good for our purposes, so in the following section, we implement AdaM to see if that has better results for our specific dataset and neural network. As far as the other neural networks go, it appears that adding a layer to the network improves the accuracy by a tiny percentage, but it also slows down the algorithm considerably and therefore does not seem altogether optimal.

def look_up_lat(state,county):
    # print(row)
    i = county
    if 'Municipio' in i: i = i.replace('Municipio',' ')
    if 'Census Area' in i: i= i.replace('Census Area',' ')
    if 'Borough' in i: i = i.replace('Borough',' ')
    add = address_lookup[(address_lookup.State==state) & (address_lookup.County ==i) ]
    return add.latitude.item()

def look_up_long(state,county):
    # print(row)
    i = county
    if 'Municipio' in i: i = i.replace('Municipio',' ')
    if 'Census Area' in i: i= i.replace('Census Area',' ')
    if 'Borough' in i: i = i.replace('Borough',' ')
    add = address_lookup[(address_lookup.State==state) & (address_lookup.County ==i) ]
    return add.longitude.item()
